    <segment id="1" parent="46" relname="span">
Myth #1:  Usability only increases development costs and lengthens development time.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="32" relname="span">

I agree with Chrusch it cost a lot more money to fix problems after development.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="30" relname="span"> A 
company has to schedule downtime and loose productivity to apply fixes to applications.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="29" relname="span"> 
Downtime has a trickle down affect on revenue;</segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="4" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> employees are not productive</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="31" relname="span"> and it is 
exposed to customer dissatisfaction</segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="23" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> because employees are not able to deliver a product.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="antithesis">


Myth #4:  Usability is really just common sense.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="43" relname="span">

Usability is NOT just common sense.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="35" relname="span"> This statement is very subjective</segment>
    <segment id="25" parent="34" relname="span"> since common 
sense does not always mean the same thing to all individuals.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="33" relname="contrast"> In the United States 
looking from left to right to safely cross the street is a good thing</segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="33" relname="contrast"> but in the United 
Kingdom it might get you hit by a car.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="10" relname="antithesis">

Myth #5:  As long as developers are familiar with guidelines, good user interfaces will be 
designed.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="44" relname="span">

Developers who are in touch with the users, their job specifications and the settings in 
which the job is carried out are on their way to developing good user interfaces.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="elaboration"> It is the 
interactions of the developer with the users that will make the guidelines make sense.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="38" relname="antithesis"> 

Myth #7:  &quot;We&apos;ll handle that in the help/training/documentation.&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="40" relname="span">

It has been my experience that users do not read documentation.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="21" relname="elaboration"> I am often reminded 
that is an IS function.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="13" relname="condition"> If they do read the documentation</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="36" relname="span"> it often does not produce the 
desired results.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="37" relname="span"> Often timeÂ’s organizations are extremely conservative</segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="16" relname="circumstance"> when it comes to 
training.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="41" relname="span"> I have found it difficult to sell a CFO on 8 hours training per employee</segment>
    <segment id="28" parent="17" relname="circumstance"> when a 
new application is implemented.</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="38" relname="conjunction"> The users can also minimize the need for training by not 
fully engaging in the process of training.</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="38" relname="conjunction"> Users will often count on power users and the 
help desk to get by.</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="38" relname="summary"> 

Help/training/documentation is definitely not the answer to usability issues.</segment>
